is debut in the [[Russian Second Division]] for [[FC Sakhalin Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk]] on 15 July 2012 in a game against [[FC Baikal Irkutsk]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Russian Football Union]]|url=http://rfspro.ru/cgi-bin/player/script2.cgi?par1=118835|title=Career Summary|date=21 April 2013|access-date=21 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140311092546/http://rfspro.ru/cgi-bin/player/script2.cgi?par1=118835|archive-date=11 March 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> He made his [[Russian Football National League]] debut for Sakhalin on 6 July 2014 in a game against [[FC Anzhi Makhachkala]].\n\n==Personal life==\nHis father [[Yuri Drozdov (footballer)|Yuri Drozdov]] is a football coach and a former player, and his younger brother Ilya Drozdov is also a footballer.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://news.sportbox.ru/Vidy_sporta/Futbol/stats/man_1315575176 Career summary by sportbox.ru] {{dead link|date=April 2020}} {{in lang|ru}}\n* {{Sportbox.ru|Futbol/Nikita-YUrievich-Drozdov-Futbol-21041992}}\n* {{Soccerway|nikita-drozdov/178803}}\n* {{FootballFacts.ru|81710<!-- -drozdov-nikita-yurevich -->}}\n\n{{FC Shinnik Yaroslavl squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Drozdov, Nikita}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Moscow]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Russian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Russian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belarus]]\n[[Category:FC Sakhalin Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk players]]\n[[Category:FC Torpedo-BelAZ Zhodino players]]\n[[Category:PFC Spartak Nalchik players]]\n[[Category:FC Shinnik Yaroslavl players]]\n[[Category:Belarusian Premier League players]]\n\n\n{{Russia-footy-midfielder-1992-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Russian football midfielder|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Eastern Slavic name|Yuryevich|Drozdov}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| image = 13 Nikita Drozdov.jpg\n| name      = Nikita Drozdov\n| fullname = Nikita Yuryevich Drozdov\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1992|04|21|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Moscow]], Russia\n| height = {{height|m=1.74}}\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[FC Shinnik Yaroslavl|Shinnik Yaroslavl]]\n| clubnumber = 13\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[FC Lokomotiv Moscow|Lokomotiv Moscow]]\n| youthyears2 = | youthclubs2 = Mikhailov SDYuSShOR Tver\n| years1 = 2011      | clubs1 = [[FC Torpedo-BelAZ Zhodino|Torpedo-BelAZ Zhodino]]           | caps1 =  1 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2012      | clubs2 = [[FC Sakhalin Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk|Sakhalin Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk]] | caps2 = 19 | goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2013\u20132014 | clubs3 = [[FC Amur-2010 Blagoveshchensk|Amur-2010 Blagoveshchensk]]   | caps3 = 23 | goals3 = 1\n| years4 = 2014\u20132015 | clubs4 = [[FC Sakhalin Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk|Sakhalin Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk]] | caps4 = 23 | goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2015\u20132017 | clubs5 = [[PFC Spartak Nalchik|Spartak Nalchik]]                      | caps5 = 60 | goals5 = 3\n| years6 = 2017\u20132018 | clubs6 = [[FC Shinnik Yaroslavl|Shinnik Yaroslavl]]                   | caps6 = 29 | goals6 = 2\n| years7 = 2018      | clubs7 = [[FC Chayka Peschanokopskoye|Chayka Peschanokopskoye]]       | caps7 =  8 | goals7 = 1\n| years8 = 2019\u2013     | clubs8 = [[FC Shinnik Yaroslavl|Shinnik Yaroslavl]]                   | caps8 = 11 | goals8 = 0\n| pcupdate = 25 May 2019\n| ntupdate = \n}}\n'''Nikita Yuryevich Drozdov''' ({{lang-ru|\u041d\u0438\u043a\u0438\u0442\u0430 \u042e\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0414\u0440\u043e\u0437\u0434\u043e\u0432}}; born 21 April 1992) is a [[Russia]]n [[association football|football]] [[midfielder]]. He plays for [[FC Shinnik Yaroslavl]].\n\n==Club career==\nHe made his debut in the [[Russian Second Division]] for [[FC Sakhalin Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk]] on 15 July 2012 in a game against [[FC Baikal Irkutsk]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Russian Football Union]]|url=http://rfspro.ru/cgi-bin/player/script2.cgi?par1=118835|title=Career Summary|date=21 April 2013|access-date=21 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140311092546/http://rfspro.ru/cgi-bin/player/script2.cgi?par1=118835|archive-date=11 March 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> He made his [[Russian Football National League]] debut for Sakhalin on 6 July 2014 in a game against [[FC Anzhi Makhachkala]].\n\n==Personal life==\nHis father [[Yuri Drozdov (footballer)|Yuri Drozdov]] is a football coach and a former player, and his younger brother Ilya Drozdov is also a footballer.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://news.sportbox.ru/Vidy_sporta/Futbol/stats/man_1315575176 Career summary by sportbox.ru]\n* {{Soccerway|nikita-drozdov/178803}}\n* {{FootballFacts.ru|81710<!-- -drozdov-nikita-yurevich -->}}\n\n{{FC Shinnik Yaroslavl squad}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Drozdov, Nikita}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Moscow]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Russian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Russian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belarus]]\n[[Category:FC Sakhalin Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk players]]\n[[Category:FC Torpedo-BelAZ Zhodino players]]\n[[Category:PFC Spartak Nalchik players]]\n[[Category:FC Shinnik Yaroslavl players]]\n[[Category:Belarusian Premier League players]]\n\n{{Russia-footy-midfielder-1992-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update sportbox.ru link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nikita_Drozdov"}
{"title_page": "2020 United States Senate election in Massachusetts", "text_new": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2020 United States Senate election in Massachusetts\n| country            = Massachusetts\n| type               = presidential\n| ongoing            = yes\n| previous_election  = 2014 United States Senate election in Massachusetts\n| previous_year      = 2014\n| next_election      = 2026 United States Senate election in Massachusetts\n| next_year          = 2026\n| election_date      = November 3, 2020\n\n| image1             = \n| nominee1           = TBD\n| party1             = Democratic Party (United States)\n| popular_vote1      = \n| percentage1        =\n\n| image2             =\n| nominee2           = TBD\n| party2             = Republican Party (United States)\n| popular_vote2      = \n| percentage2        =\n\n| map_image          = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = County results\n| title              = U.S. Senator\n| before_election    = [[Ed Markey]]\n| before_party       = Democratic Party (United States)\n| after_election     = \n| after_party        = \n}}\n{{Elections in Massachusetts}}\n\nThe '''2020 United States Senate election in Massachusetts''' will be held November 3, 2020, to elect a [[List of United States senators from Massachusetts|United States Senator from Massachusetts]], concurrently with the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 U.S. presidential election]], as well as [[2020 United States Senate elections|other elections]] to the United States Senate in other states and [[2020 United States House of Representatives elections|elections]] to the [[United States House of Representatives]] and various [[2020 United States elections#State elections|state]] and [[2020 United States elections#Local elections|local elections]]. U.S. Representative [[Joe Kennedy III]] is running against Incumbent [[Ed Markey]] for the Democratic nomination.\n\n==Democratic primary==\nThe state primary election will take place on September 1, 2020.<ref name=\":0\">https://www.sec.state.ma.us/CalendarWeb/Pages/MonthWeekCalendar.aspx</ref>\n\n===Candidates===\n\n====Declared====\n*[[Ed Markey]], incumbent U.S. Senator<ref>{{cite news|last=Guzman|first=Dan|title=Markey Confirms Plans To Run For Re-Election In 2020|url=http://www.wbur.org/news/2018/10/05/markey-2020-re-election|publisher=WBUR|date=October 5, 2018|accessdate=November 14, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Joe Kennedy III]], incumbent U.S. Representative for [[Massachusetts's 4th congressional district]]<ref>{{cite article|title=Joe Kennedy Officially Announces Decision To Run For US Senate|publisher=[[WBZ-TV]]|url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2019/09/21/joe-kennedy-congressman-campaign-announcement-us-senate-ed-markey/|access-date=September 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Potential====\n*[[Maura Healey]], [[Massachusetts Attorney General]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/news/politics/2018/11/28/ed-markey-2020-primary-challenge |title=Ed Markey: \u2018I do my best\u2019 |last=DeCosta-Klipa |first=Nik |date=November 28, 2018 |work=Boston.com |language=en-US |accessdate=November 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"wbsm\">{{Cite news |url=https://wbsm.com/how-many-will-challenge-sen-markey-in-2020-opinion/|title=HOW MANY WILL CHALLENGE SEN. MARKEY IN 2020? |last=McCarthy |first=Chris|work=wbsm.com |language=en-US |accessdate=April 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*Scott Lang, former mayor of [[New Bedford, Massachusetts|New Bedford]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Murphy|first1=Matt|title=Former New Bedford mayor eyeing possible U.S. Senate bid|url=https://www.southcoasttoday.com/news/20190621/former-new-bedford-mayor-eyeing-possible-us-senate-bid|newspaper=The Standard-Times|date=June 21, 2019|accessdate=June 21, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Juana Matias]], former state representative and candidate for [[Massachusetts's 3rd congressional district]] in 2018<ref name=\"Kennedy\">{{cite news|last1=McGrane|first1=Victoria|title=After Mike Capuano\u2019s defeat, is Ed Markey a primary target for 2020?|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/11/27/after-mike-capuano-defeat-markey-primary-target-for/MGYuhJQTzRhbvNFsoxb9wK/story.html|newspaper=The Boston Globe|date=November 27, 2018|accessdate=November 30, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Michelle Wu]], Boston city councilor<ref>{{cite news|last1=McGrane|first1=Victoria|title=After Mike Capuano\u2019s defeat, is Ed Markey a primary target for 2020?|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/11/27/after-mike-capuano-defeat-markey-primary-target-for/MGYuhJQTzRhbvNFsoxb9wK/story.html|newspaper=The Boston Globe|date=November 27, 2018|accessdate=November 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Withdrawn====\n*[[Shannon Liss-Riordan]], labor attorney<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/01/17/metro/labor-lawyer-shannon-liss-riordan-drops-out-us-senate-primary/|title=Labor lawyer Shannon Liss-Riordan drops out of US Senate primary \u2013 The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com}}</ref>\n*Steve Pemberton, chief human resources officer for Workhuman<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tiernan|first1=Erin|title=Pemberton drops of out of 2020 Senate race against Markey|url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2019/10/14/pemberton-drops-of-out-of-2020-senate-race-against-markey/|newspaper=Boston Herald|date=October 14, 2019|accessdate=October 14, 2019}}</ref>\n*Allen Waters, perennial candidate<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20191216/providence-native-drops-mass-senate-bid-to-challenge-reed|title=Providence native drops Mass. Senate bid to challenge Reed|first=Katherine|last=Gregg|website=providencejournal.com}}</ref>\n\n====Declined====\n*[[Seth Moulton]], former 2020 presidential candidate and incumbent U.S. Representative for [[Massachusetts's 6th congressional district]] ([[2020 United States House of Representatives elections in Massachusetts#District 6|running for re-election]])<ref>{{cite news|last=Burns|first=Alexander|title=Democrats Embrace Liberal Insurgents, Demanding New Face for Party|url=https